ed to reconsider how blessed handles layering—elements render in append order, so if I append parents before children, they'll naturally stack correctly. The border styling looks good for a wireframe view, though I should verify how blessed renders borders with the line type.\n\nFor the color system, blessed supports named colors and RGB values, so I'll need to convert the spatial layout colors to blessed's color format.\n\nI also need to update the dependency check to include blessed alongside playwright, and clarify that playwright is still required since the TUI needs to fetch and parse the layout JSON from the actual page render. Writing the renderTui function... Writing the TUI rendering function... Building the blessed box layout... Finishing the render call and closing out the function. I'm realizing I need to handle the blessed dependency more carefully—it should only be installed when the `--tui` flag is used, but following the existing bootstrap pattern, I'll add it to `ensureDependencies()` so it's available before any command parsing happens. This means blessed gets installed even if not needed, but it keeps the pattern consistent.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the box rendering details. Blessed borders take up space, reducing the content area by 2 characters in each dimension. I could conditionally add borders based on box size, but I'll keep it simple and always include them since the task asks for labeled boxes at proportional positions.\n\nFor minimum dimensions, I need at least 3 columns and 2 rows to make a visible bordered box. Now I'm ready to write the implementation, starting with the dependency check, argument parsing, and then the main layout logic.\n\nI need to figure out where to branch in the main function—after computing the tree, I'll check if TUI mode is enabled and either render the terminal interface or output JSON as usual.\n\nWriting the implementation... I'm realizing the flow should work—`renderTui` gets called in the try block, then the browser closes in the finally block, but the blessed terminal interface keeps the event loop alive until the user presses 'q' and exits. The key is that `renderTui` doesn't need to await anything; it just sets up the UI and returns, letting the blessed screen handle the rest. etes, then `browser.close()` runs in the finally block, and the process stays alive because blessed maintains active handles until the user presses 'q' to exit. This is exactly what we want.\n\nNow I'm planning the specific edits to make: first, I'll add blessed to the dependency installation section, then modify the main function to set up the blessed UI and handle the keyboard input for graceful shutdown.\n\nAdding blessed installation logic... Now I'm planning out the remaining edits to complete the TUI implementation—adding the incompatibility check between `--tui` and `--output`, creating the rendering function, and updating the result handling logic to route to the TUI when that flag is set.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6807,"cache_read_input_tokens":21059,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6807},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9230af59-663e-42ce-8313-c2b8db0a74f8","uuid":"4e9cc9d2-90ac-42b5-80ec-27cfad257dda"}
